<P>
14 MARCH 1996 09:03 HOURS -- 09:36 HOURS
<P>BEGIN INTERCEPT: 09:03 Static. Rusty? Static. Rusty, can you hear me? Static. Rusty? Are you on the satellite phone? Static. Hum. Electronic shriek. Click. Line dead.

<P>09:05 UNIDENTIFIED MALE: Good morning, Mr. Vice President.
<P>VPOTUS: Good morning, Dick.
<P>UN.MALE: I have good news, Mr. Vice President. Steve Forbes is pulling out of the race.
<P>VPOTUS: That is good news. All along I've said that he was only Republican who could beat us. Dynamic speaker. Good with the crowds.
<P>UN.MALE: Yes, well. The point is, sir, that that leaves Bob Dole the Republican nominee. We'd like to start getting out the big guns. And we were wondering -- 
<P>VPOTUS: You want me to give an environmental policy address?
<P>UN.MALE: Well . . .
<P>VPOTUS: Introduce new crime legislation?
<P>UN.MALE: Actually . . .
<P>VPOTUS: Talk tough on trade?
<P>UN.MALE: Sir, what we'd like you to do -- and this is just phase one, here -- is publicly call Ross Perot a chicken and dare him to run for President.
<P>VPOTUS: You want me to dare Ross Perot to run?
<P>UN.MALE: And call him a chicken, sir.
<P>VPOTUS: Um . . . I'm not sure . . .
<P>UN.MALE: We've got you booked on Larry King next week. Think it over, sir. Click. Line dead. 

<P>09:17 FLOTUS: Good morning, Al.
<P>VPOTUS: Good morning, Hillary.
<P>FLOTUS: I just called to let you know that the new NBC News/Wall Street Journal poll has us up over Dole by 11 points.
<P>VPOTUS: I read that. That's good news.
<P>FLOTUS: But Bill's negatives are in the low forties.
<P>VPOTUS: Yeah, well . . .
<P>FLOTUS: And my negatives are in the low seventies.
<P>VPOTUS: Yeah, well . . .
<P>FLOTUS: You have negatives in the low teens.
<P>VPOTUS: I've heard that.
<P>FLOTUS: Watch yourself. Click. Line dead. 

<P>09:22 UNIDENTIFIED MALE: Hello, sir.
<P>VPOTUS: Hi, Chris.
<P>SENDODD: Sir, I'm just calling you to give you a heads up on our Senate re-election plans. We feel that the only way to regain control of the Senate is to set ourselves apart, to draw a contrast between, say, a Democrat and Newt Gingrich.
<P>VPOTUS: Sounds great.
<P>SENDODD: And it is great. It'll work. We also might have to triangulate in the other direction.
<P>VPOTUS: How so?
<P>SENDODD: You know, things like ``Stop President Dole'' -- that kind of thing.
<P>VPOTUS: Okay. I see where this is going.
<P>SENDODD: And NAFTA. But -- 
<P>VPOTUS: NAFTA?
<P>SENDODD: The unions, sir. They're making us.
<P>VPOTUS: Making you?
<P>SENDODD: Hey, you pour $35 million into the Democratic Congressional Campaign, you can make me squeal like a pig, you know what I'm saying?
<P>VPOTUS: I guess.
<P>SENDODD: And we may run an ad like ``Clinton's trying to steal your Medicare.''
<P>VPOTUS: What?
<P>SENDODD: Sir, it's politics, okay.
<P>VPOTUS: But the upcoming budget battle is going to result in a compromise. We're going to sign a balanced budget, with Medicare cuts.
<P>SENDODD: I know. I'm all for it.
<P>VPOTUS: You are?
<P>SENDODD: How else are we going to get the
Senate back? Click. Line dead. 

<P>09:33 SLOTUS: Hi, honey!
<P>VPOTUS: Hey, Tip!
<P>SLOTUS: I need you to run something by the ethics person in the West Wing. I just got the most gorgeous flower arrangement from a reporter and I want to know if it's okay to keep it.
<P>VPOTUS: Wait a sec. Back up.
<P>SLOTUS: I called the florist, who priced the arrangement at around $100, but it's an election year and I want everything to be squeaky clean.
<P>VPOTUS: Who sent you flowers?
<P>SLOTUS: Jim Stewart. So can I -- 
<P>VPOTUS: Who's he?
<P>SLOTUS: Honestly, Al. You're so out of the loop. He wrote the new book Blood Sport, about Whitewater, and I -- 
<P>VPOTUS: So how come he's sending you flowers?
<P>SLOTUS: Because he couldn't have written the book by himself. Click. Line dead. 
<P>END INTERCEPT.
<P>
Your Pal,  Al
<P>
</body>
</html>
