<head><title>For The Record -- NR</title></head>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H2> For The Record </H2></CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
August 14 1995
<P>
<P><LI>Announcing he was quitting as <B>Bob Dole</B>'s South Carolina co-chairman to
take same job with Sen. <B>Phil Gramm</B>'s presidential campaign, former congressman
<B>Arthur Ravenel</B> cited as reason Dole's chief of staff, <B>Sheila Burke</B>: ``She's a
former liberal Democrat, and she's still liberal, and it's said she has a great deal of influence over
Senator Dole.'' Noting recent outbreak of articles about Burke's influence on Dole -- including
<B>John Fund</B>'s in <I>Wall Street Journal</I> and <B>Rich Lowry</B>'s in <I>NR --
Washington Post</I> ran story with headline ``Dole's Chief of Staff Is Magnet for Criticism.''
<I>Post</I> also quoted conservative activist <B>Paul Weyrich</B>: ``I was the one to fire the
first salvo. Anything good we've gotten from Dole has been over her dead body.'' . . . Dole,
though, has picked up support from unexpected quarter: Arkansas chicken mogul and former
<B>Clinton</B> buddy <B>Don Tyson</B>, whose spokesman says ``Bill Clinton's election is
the worst thing that has ever happened to Tyson Foods and the state of Arkansas.'' . . . Air of
inevitability to entry of <B>Newt Gingrich</B> into presidential race? Gingrich's recent
emphasis to interviewers that Majority Leader <B>Dick Armey</B> runs House on day-to-day
basis may be Speaker's way of preparing colleagues. Newt will take the plunge, says columnist
<B>Cal Thomas</B>, who notes he wagered $50 with Heritage Foundation President <B>Ed
Feulner</B> -- a bet Feulner wanted to withdraw after hearing a Gingrich address. . . .
<B>Phyllis Schlafly</B>, chairman of Republican National Coalition for Life, says five GOP
presidential candidates have signed pledge to support Republican platform's pro-life plank: Phil
Gramm, <B>Pat Buchanan</B>, Rep. <B>Bob Dornan</B> (Calif.), <B>Alan Keyes</B>, and
Sen. <B>Richard Lugar</B> (Ind.). . . . On Democratic side, New York Times clearly worried
about third-party threat to Clinton -- it ran front-page article with unusually negative quotes
about potential Clinton rival <B>Jesse Jackson</B>. Sample: <B>Deneen Winn</B> said, ``. . .
he's better at giving speeches than doing anything.'' . . . Buckpac alert: Former Connecticut
Senator and Governor <B>Lowell Weicker</B> told <I>USA Today</I> he knows it won't be
easy but he's thinking about presidential race as independent and -- seeking to stir more
controversy? -- asserted: ``I'm no damn fool.''
<BR>


<P><LI>Behind the scenes at special Senate committee investigating Whitewater: Serious
consideration given to calling former Whitewater special counsel <B>Bob Fiske</B> as witness.
Fiske said he found no evidence that White House aide <B>Vincent Foster</B> was worried
about Whitewater when he committed suicide. In Foster's handwritten notes which were
available to Fiske, however, the committee found plenty. Fiske was initially recommended for
counsel's spot by ex-Clinton counsel <B>Bernard Nussbaum</B>, who has emerged in
committee hearings as leader of efforts to block police from searching Foster's office. In private
practice, Nussbaum and Fiske were friends and gave each other client referrals. . . . Whitewater
panel member Sen. <B>Frank Murkowski</B> (R., Alaska) hit front pages by holding up
Foster's briefcase to show Clinton aides couldn't have missed suicide note inside. He also
prompted first Watergate-style malapropism from defensive Democrats. Thrashing around with
briefcase, indignant Clinton defender Sen. <B>John Kerry</B> (D., Mass.) announced -- in a
quote gleefully used by conservative journalists -- ``When you pull the files out, the briefcase
closes essentially shut. You can't see in it. I can't see in it. Nobody could see in it.''
<BR>


<P><LI>National Journalism Center, which offers 12-week internships for college students,
starts fall session September 25, with application deadline September 8. Contact <B>M. Stanton
Evans</B> or <B>Mal Kline</B> at 800 Maryland Ave., N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002. Phone
202-544-1333, fax 544-5368. . . . <B>Les Lenkowsky</B>, Hudson Institute president, says
<B>Wm. F. Buckley Jr.</B> will present <B>Doolittle</B> award for national-security
contributions to <B>Barry Goldwater</B> at National Press Club on September 28; Sen.
<B>Sam Nunn</B> and former VP <B>Dan Quayle</B> also on program.
<BR>


<P><LI>North Korea dictator <B>Kim Jong Il</B> is back in view, and Asia experts say (this
week, anyway) he has consolidated power. . . . Vatican considering as future archbishop of
Saigon Msgr. <B>Nguyen Van Thuan</B>, whom Hanoi hates as anti-Communist nephew of
former South Vietnam President <B>Ngo Dinh Diem</B>. . . . <I>Washington Times</I>'s
<B>Bill Gertz</B> reports Moscow is trying to slow U.S. ABM development because it fears
competition with Russian missiles in international arms markets. . . . Prodded by Sen. <B>Jesse
Helms</B> (R., N.C.) and Rep. <B>Robert Torricelli</B> (D., N.J.), State Department is
threatening Nicaragua with aid cutoff if it does not compensate citizens for property seized by
former Sandinista regime. . . . Two British detectives have written book claiming American
surgeon <B>Francis Tumblety</B> was suspect in four London murders and may have been the
real <B>Jack the Ripper</B>.
<BR>


<P><LI>Columnists' notes: <B>Hillary Clinton</B> says she hopes her new syndicated column
will make her more like <B>Eleanor Roosevelt</B> and awaken everyone to the ``human
dimension of our lives.'' . . . Disgruntled by delays on conservative legislation, <I>Wall Street
Journal</I>'s <B>Paul Gigot</B> compares U.S. Senate to ``daily running of 100 Pamplona
bulls without the discipline.'' . . . For Jews worried about too much assimilation by American
culture, <I>New York Times</I> columnist <B>William Safire</B> has startling statistic that
may prove opposite: bagels now outsell donuts.     -- OCD
</BODY>
