<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Small Business:Labor Watch, Issue 17</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<P>
<center><h3>Small Business Survival Foundation</h3>
<img src="/sbsc/hdr-lw.gif" alt="Header">
<h2>Labor Watch, Issue 17</h2></center>
<hr><p>
<ul>
<li><a href="#one">The NLRB, Unabashed Advocate For Big Labor</a><br>
<li><a href="#two">Proposed Legislation Strengthens <i>Beck</i> Decision</a><br>
<li><a href="#three">The Little Theatre That Could</a><br>
<li><a href="#four">New Labor Party Imports European Model For Economic Disaster</a><br>
<li><a href="#five">Labor Watch Factoid</a><br>
</ul><p>
<hr>
<blockquote>
<B>June 20, 1996<BR>
</B>
<P>
<a name="one"></a>
<B><i>The NLRB <FONT FACE="Typographic Ext">,</FONT> Unabashed
Advocate for Big Labor<BR>
</B></i>
<P>
Here is the ultimate proof that Organized Labor has received what
it paid for <FONT FACE="Typographic Ext">,</FONT> a National Labor
Relations Board (NLRB) that will satisfy the union agenda in every
instance.
<P>
Last week, NLRB Chairman Gould cast aside all sense of propriety,
decorum and lip service to impartiality by publicly denouncing
the TEAM Act, a bill to promote workplace cooperation.  Using
such rhetoric terming the bill &quot;classic Republican overkill,&quot;
 while renaming the measure the &quot;Employer Domination Act,&quot;
Gould left the arena of ideas and wholly joined the AFL-CIO propaganda
machine.
<P>
NLRB board members are judges.  The Labor Board is not supposed
to be the policy arm of the Clinton Administration, the Democratic
National Committee, nor the AFL-CIO. Gould has not only chosen
to embroil himself in a major legislative controversy, he's proven
himself an unabashed advocate of big labor rather than an impartial
judge of the law.
<P>
Just last month, as reported in <I>Labor Watch,</I> the Clinton
NLRB reversed long-standing law by giving unions the power to
shut down businesses in their effort to unionize separate companies.
 That case, involving a construction firm, established the new
rule of law that unions are free to strike, harass, and destroy
companies with which they have no bargaining relationship, so
long as the unions claim they are entitled to the type of work
in question; i.e., as part of a work preservation effort.
<P>
As Bill Gould showed last week, what John Sweeney and labor leaders
want from the NLRB, John Sweeney and the labor leaders get.<BR>
<BR>
<P>
<a name="two"> </a>
<i><B>Proposed Legislation Strengthens Beck Decision
<BR>
</B></i>
<P>
Workers will have a right to know how labor leaders spend their
union dues under new legislation introduced by House Republicans.
 The Worker Right To Know Act, H.R. 3580, strengthens provisions
under the <I>Beck</I> decision, which allows workers to obtain
a rebate of the portion of their dues not related to collective
bargaining.
<P>
Key provisions under the Worker Right to Know Act:
<P>
<FONT FACE="Typographic Ext">-</FONT>Require unions to get annual
written authorization from each worker before accepting or demanding
payment of money  not spent for collective bargaining and contract
administration; i.e., for political purposes;
<P>
<FONT FACE="Typographic Ext">-</FONT> Establish an independent
auditor to determine the percentage of dues money that is spent
on collective bargaining or noncollective bargaining;
<P>
<FONT FACE="Typographic Ext">-</FONT> Prohibit unions from forcing
workers to join and pay dues as a condition of employment;
<P>
<FONT FACE="Typographic Ext">-</FONT> Allow workers to participate
in a union without paying the portion of dues that goes towards
non-collective bargaining activities; and
<P>
<FONT FACE="Typographic Ext">-</FONT> Require unions to report
annually to the Department of Labor on how dues money is spent.
<P>
AFL-CIO President, John J. Sweeney labeled the new bill as &quot;a
calculated effort to chill our exercise of First Amendment rights
to inform members and the public about attacks this Congress is
leading against working families.&quot;
<P>
In reality, the legislation simply gives workers more protections
and say over how their union dues is spent.<BR>
<BR>
<P>
<a name="three"></a>
<B><i>The Little Theater that Could<BR>
</B></i>
<P>
A small, nonprofit children's theater in New York City could boast
of standing-room-only if not for the fact that the crowds have
been union pickets.  The New Victory Theater on 42nd Street has
been the target of big Broadway unions who are trying to muscle
their way on stage.
<P>
New Victor uses nonunion workers, which helps keep ticket prices
down.  The theater's practice has not received warm reviews from
the labor unions, including ushers, makeup artists, and press
agents.  They fear that potential new neighbor, Disney, will follow
New Victory's lead when they move in down the block.  In the meantime,
the show will go on, union pickets and all.<BR>
<P>
<a name="four"></a>
<i><B>New Labor Party Imports European Model for Economic
Disaster<BR>
</B></i>
<P>
As reported in the June 6 edition of <I>Labor Watch</I>, a new
American Labor Party met June 6 - 9 in Cleveland, Ohio.  The Labor
Party agreed to 16 principles that they would pursue as part of
their legislative and political agenda.  <I>Labor Watch</I> will
periodically list these principles <FONT FACE="Typographic Ext">,</FONT>
in this edition, we highlight Principle 6:
<P>
<CENTER>Less Work, More Money<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
The Labor Party calls for amending the Fair Labor Standards Act
to:
<P>
<FONT FACE="Typographic Ext">-</FONT> A 32-hour, 4-day work week
(without loss of pay or benefits).
<P>
<FONT FACE="Typographic Ext">-</FONT> Provide a minimum of double-time
pay for all hours worked over 32 hours a week and 8 hours a day.
<P>
<FONT FACE="Typographic Ext">-</FONT> Forbid compulsory overtime.
<P>
<FONT FACE="Typographic Ext">-</FONT> An hour off with pay for
every 2 hours of overtime.
<P>
<FONT FACE="Typographic Ext">-</FONT> 20 mandatory paid vacation
days plus all federal holidays.
<P>
<FONT FACE="Typographic Ext">-</FONT> One year paid leave for every
7 years of work.
<P>
Together with the Labor Party's call for universal health care,
paid family leave, free child and elder care for all, and a constitutional
requirement that all Americans be guaranteed a job at (a minimum)
of $10 per hour adjusted for inflation <FONT FACE="Typographic Ext">,</FONT>
they claim these proposals will help create millions of new jobs.
<BR>
<P>
<a name="five"></a>
<i> <B>Labor Watch Factoid</B></i>
<P>
 
<P>
Congressman Pete Hoekstra discovered that Clinton's AmeriCorps
has awarded a $400,000 contract to the AFL-CIO to provide financial
management training to grantees.<BR>
<P>
source: Rep. Pete Hoekstra - U.S. House<BR>
<BR>
<P>
<I><B>Correction</B></I>
<P>
The June 13, 1996 edition of <I>Labor Watch</I> incorrectly referred
to Cleveland, Ohio Mayor Michael R. White as the mayor of Columbus,
Ohio.  The Honorable Michael R.White is indeed the mayor of Cleveland,
<p>
<BR>
