<HEAD>
<TITLE>Small Business: Labor Watch, Issue 15</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR ="#FFFFFF">
<center><h3>Small Business Survival Foundation</h3>
<img src="/sbsc/hdr-lw.gif" alt="Header">
<h2>Labor Watch, Issue 15</h2></center>
<hr><p>
<ul>
<li><a href="#one">An American Labor Party Will Be Officially Launched Early June</a><br>
<li><a href="#two">Going Postal</a><br>
<li><a href="#three">Teaching Discord</a><br>
<li><a href="#four">Stand For Clinton Rally Brings Out The Left</a><br>
<li><a href="#five">Minimum Wage Quote</a><br>
</ul><hr><p>
<blockquote>
<B>June 6, 1996<BR>
</B>
<P>
<a name="one"></a>
<i><B>An American Labor Party Will be Officially Launched
Early June<BR></i>
</B>
<P>
Some 1200 delegates representing local unions, central labor councils
and national unions will soon meet in Cleveland, Ohio to officially
announce the formation of an American labor party.  While the
name of the party has yet to be decided upon, its agenda and political
strategy has been well conceived.
<P>
The labor party will not endorse candidates (it believes the Democrat
Party has moved too far to the right) or run candidates for office
for several years, but it does intend to be a major political
force on issue advocacy and use the party to &quot;frame the nation's
political debate in terms of class <FONT FACE="Typographic Ext">,</FONT>
a broad working class against irresponsible, unacceptable corporate
power.&quot;  According to a May 27 article written for <I><B>In
These Times</B></I> (a twice-monthly left-leaning newspaper),
labor party advocates claim that its union supporters now number
over 1 million people <FONT FACE="Typographic Ext">,</FONT> or
6% of the labor movement.
<P>
According to the article, the labor party's statements of principle
include the following <FONT FACE="Typographic Ext">,</FONT> &quot;a
constitutional right to a job at a living wage; an income stability
fund to protect workers against job dislocation and downsizing
(see <I><B>Labor Watch</B></I> May 10, Issue 12 on New Jersey
proposal); free higher education for all; assurances of basic
social needs (single-payer health care, longer paid vacations,
affordable day care); and shorter work time.&quot;  The principles
also include union dominance in the workplace and &quot;just transition
to a non-polluting economic system and genuine equality of opportunity.&quot;
<P>
Interestingly, the party's chief organizers and advocates say
that they've made a major effort to &quot;minimize the influence
of small sectarian left groups.&quot;
<P>
Lastly, both labor party organizers and the AFL-CIO see their
goals as complimentary as the agenda of the new party is &quot;not
all that different&quot; from the unions.<BR>
<P>
<a name="two"></a>
<B><i>Going Postal<BR></i>
</B>
<P>
A new theory behind workplace violence was unveiled at the recent
meeting of the National Academy of Arbitrators <FONT FACE="Typographic Ext">,</FONT>
and all indications are that attendees may be in need of having
their heads examined.
<P>
Psychologists and unions now attribute incidents of employee violence
to failures in the workplace <FONT FACE="Typographic Ext">,</FONT>
<U>not</U> &quot;bad people,&quot; or &quot;crazy workers.&quot;
 For example, workplace factors that lead to violence can include
an employee reaction to unbearable workplace stress, such as downsizing
or the interaction with a person, or a situation.
<P>
While unions were quick to pin the blame of this serious issue
directly on human resource managers and employers, they were slow
to provide helpful solutions to the problem.  Unions denounced
the use of preventative measures, such as psychological profiles,
to help identify potentially violent employees.  According to
an official with the public-employee union American Federation
of State County and Municipal Employees (AFSCME), lots of profiles
of violent employees &quot;sound like the profile of a good union
steward.&quot;<BR>
<P>
<a name="three"></a>
<i><B>Teaching Discord<BR>
</B></i>
<P>
At its 1995 convention, the National Education Association (NEA)
again defined itself as one of the leaders of the &quot;Big(ger)
Government Coalition.&quot;  Some of its resolutions include:
<P>
Endorsed single-payer Canadian-style health care;
<P>
Endorsed statehood for the District of Columbia;
<P>
Endorsed Gay and Lesbian History Month;
<P>
Denounced giving parents the right to choose their children's
schools;
<P>
Denounced home-schooling; and
<P>
Denounced a moment of silence in schools.
<P>
The NEA contributed $4.1 million in PAC funds to Democrats between
1993 and 1995.<BR>
<P>
<a name="four"></a><i>
<B> Stand for Clinton Rally Brings Out the Left<BR>
</B></i>
<P>
Unions weren't the only members of the radical fringe working
the crowd at last Saturday's Stand for Children rally.
<P>
Mike Golash stood near the rally stage hawking <U>Challenge</U>,
a publication of the Revolutionary Communist Progressive Labor
Party.  Its headline: &quot;CAPITALISM NO PLACE FOR KIDS.&quot;
<P>
According to a <I><B>Washington Post</B></I> report, Golash said,
&quot;What I hope to see is millions and millions of people warming
to the communist ideals <FONT FACE="Typographic Ext">,</FONT>
abolishing the wage system, ending racism and sexism, ending child
exploitation.  I see people realizing that we can take power through
revolution from the capitalists, and we can build a new society
based on production for equality, not production for profits.&quot;
<P>
The <I><B>Post</B></I> goes on to quote Golash as saying, &quot;Oh,
in the revolution, most of those people [conservatives] will be
destroyed.  They'll take up arms against us <FONT FACE="Typographic Ext">,</FONT>
there'll be a war, a civil war.  And they will be, you know, gotten
rid of, basically.&quot;<BR>
<P>
<a name="five"></a><i>
 <B>Minimum Wage Quote<BR>
</B></i>
<P>
&quot;I oppose not only an increase in the starting wage, but
a mandated starting wage period. It represents another death nail
in the coffin of the United States' free enterprise system.&quot;
<p>
Taalib-Din Uqdah
<br>
SBSC Business Leader,  May 15, 1996 before the U.S. House of Representatives
Small Business Committee<BR>
<BR><p>
<center>| <a href="/sbsc/laborwatch/welcome.html">Back</a> |</center>
