<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Small Business: Labor Watch, Issue 2</TITLE>


</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><h3>Small Business Survival Foundation</h3>
<img src="/sbsc/hdr-lw.gif" alt="Header" >
<h2>Labor Watch, Issue 2</h2></center>

<hr><P>
<ul>
<li><a href="#one">Another Clinton Payback - Putting Unions First</a><br>
<li><a href="#two">A Dose of Democracy - Send in the U.N.?</a><br>
<li><a href="#three">BIG LABOR'S Real Agenda: Corporate Campaign Exposed</a><br>
<li><a href="#four">Letter Carriers Are Big Winners in Oregon Vote-by-Mail Election</a><br>
<li><a href="#five">AFL-CIO Charged with Crossing the Line in Campaign Activity</a><br>
</ul>
<p>
<HR><a name="one"></a>
<blockquote>
<i><B>Another Clinton Payback - Putting Unions First</B></i>
<P>
Vice President Al Gore paid homage to assembled union leaders
at their annual Bal Harbour, Florida retreat last week.  Mr. Gore
promptly delivered the President's response to union demands.
 The following is a partial score card:
<P><pre>
<i>Union Demand</i>   				<i>Administration Position</i>
<P><hr><p>
Veto OSHA Reform			Veto Promised
<P>
Support Minimum Wage Increase		Support Assured
<P>
Veto Davis-Bacon Repeal			Veto Promised
<P>
Veto Workplace Cooperation Bill		Veto Promised
<P>
Appeal Adverse Ruling on Striker	Appeal in the Works
<P>
Replacement Executive Order		Announced at Last Year's 
					Meeting  
</pre>
<hr>
<P>
The AFL-CIO has set March 25th for its vote on whether to endorse
President Clinton for reelection.
<P><a name="two"></a>
 <B>A Dose of Democracy - Send in the U.N.?</B>
<P>
The Laborers International Union has a rich history of corruption.
 The Justice Department thinks it can change that with a healthy
dose of democracy.  The union has agreed to its first rank-and-file
election of officers, scheduled for September.
<P>
The Laborers leadership agreed to reforms in order to rid the
union of its tainted past of corruption and links to organized
crime, and to avoid a government takeover of its operations. 
The old system was so fraught with cronyism and fraud that a federal
overseer must now spend months devising election rules, teach
union members how to exercise rights they did not previously enjoy,
and monitor 500 local meetings where convention delegates are
selected.
<P><a name="three"></a>
<i><B>BIG LABOR'S Real Agenda:</B></i>
<P>
<B>Corporate Campaign Exposed</B>
<P>
Apparently organized labor's concerted effort to bring corporate
America to its knees devolves to the downright petty.  Construction
unions in Boston are trying to shame the Palm Restaurant into
paying prix fixe when a la carte makes more sense.
<P>
The unions are not picketing the site of the new restaurant. 
They are not attacking the company's building permits or filing
frivolous lawsuits.  They are not even trying to block financing
for the project by threatening local bankers.  Rather, <I>The
Wall Street Journal</I> reports that the building trades unions
are threatening the decor of the restaurant to force the Palm
to fire a non-union contractor and submit to build on the union's
terms (at a 38% premium).
<P>
Hoping to decimate the collection of celebrity caricatures which
adorn the walls of each Palm location, the unions are begging
local notables to pull their faces from the walls of the Palm.
 Several have acquiesced  - Sens. Ted Kennedy and John Kerry,
<I>Atlantic Monthly </I>editor Jack Beatty, and legal beagle Alan
Dershowitz.  Some, less sympathetic types, might consider this
urban renewal.
<P><a name="four"></a>
<i><B>Letter Carriers Are Big Winners in Oregon Vote-by-Mail Election</B></i>
<P>
According to a <I>Washington Times</I>  mention entitled &quot;Delivering
the Vote,&quot; the labor unions were quite pleased (in more ways
than one) with Oregon's recent special election.  The newspaper
notes:
<P>
&quot;The National Association of Letter Carriers (NALC), AFL-CIO
carried two headlines in its newsletter concerning Ron Wyden's
recent election to the Senate.  &quot;Letter Carriers Major Factor
in Wyden Oregon Senate Win,&quot; the NALC bulletin said.  &quot;Vote-by-Mail
Balloting Receives Praise.&quot;   
<P><a name="five"></a>
<i><B>AFL-CIO Charged with Crossing the Line in Campaign Activity</B></i>
<P>
The National Republican Congressional Committee (NRCC) filed a
complaint last week with the Federal Election Commission (FEC)
charging that &quot;PROJECT '95&quot; - an AFL-CIO special campaign
 - violated the law because its goals were to defeat House Republicans
using union members' dues.  The NRCC charges that the AFL-CIO
was engrossed in &quot;active electioneering&quot; in Federal
campaigns.  House Republicans on the PROJECT '95 target list were
saturated with radio and television advertising, and other outreach
activities in their congressional districts.  According to the
NRCC though, PROJECT '95 was coordinated with the Democratic Party
- the list of targeted House Republicans was distributed at a
key meeting of assembled House Democrats.
<P>
&quot;The AFL-CIO's PROJECT '95...misused the dues paid by the
hard-working men and women who belong to the member unions,&quot;
states a NRCC press release.  The NRCC also charges that AFL-CIO
chief John Sweeny's proclamation that the union will use $35 million
of its treasury to defeat Republicans in 1996 also violates federal
election law.
</blockquote><P><br><p>
<center>| <a href="/sbsc/des.html">Back to SBSF</a> |</center>

</BODY>

