<html><head><title>SBSC Issues:  Independent Contractors</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><h2>Independent Contractors</h2><hr width="45%" size="4"><P>
</center>
On June 30, 1995, Representative Jon Christensen (R-NE) introduced
H.R. 1972, the &quot;Independent Contractor Tax Simplification
Act of 1995.&quot;  This piece of legislation seeks to establish
clear criteria for defining the tax status for the self-employed
as independent contractor.  Currently, the IRS subjects numerous
individuals who work autonomously to an infamous 20-factor test.
<P>
 This test challenges the tax status of many of those who choose
to work independently.  Additionally, the ambiguous, subjective
20-factor test may reclassify independent contractors as employees,
causing back-taxes and penalties for the business contracting
with the individual.
<P>
Rep. Christensen's bill would clearly state who is not an employee,
and it allows independent contractors to avoid the 20-factor test.
<P>
 Currently H.R. 1972 is in the House Ways and Means Committee.
<P>
Despite large support from the small business community and many
legislators, this bill requires a continuous effort to ensure
passage.  For more information, see Karen Kerrigan's article &quot;IRS
should revise contract-worker tests.&quot;
<P>
Send a letter to the following Senators and Congressman expressing your support of the Independent Contractor Tax Simplification Act:<p>

<a href="/sbsc/l-ic-gephardt.html">Minority Leader Richard Gephardt</a><br>
<a href="/sbsc/l-ic-daschle.html">Minority Leader Tom Daschle</a><br>
<a href="/sbsc/l-ic-ford.html">Minority Whip Wendell Ford</a><p>

You can also print out a letter to send to your <a href="/sbsc/l-ic-congress.txt">Congressman</a> or <a href="/sbsc/l-ic-senate.txt">Senator</a>.<p>
<br>



