Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>"Intellectual Scandal" Uncovered By Evans</title>
</head>

<body>

<h2>"Intellectual Scandal" Uncovered By Evans</h2>
<h4>Salvatori Speaker Urges Understanding of Our Founding</h4>

Before a packed house of 400 college students from across the country, <b>M. Stanton Evans</b> urged students to remember the religious roots of our liberty as understood by America's Founding Fathers. The student event was sponsored by Young America's Foundation and the Fund for American Studies at  the Conservative Political Action Conference in Washington, D.C on February 18. Mr. Evans is the Henry  Salvatori Distinguished Lecturer for 1994-1995, and will be sponsored by Young America's Foundation to  speak before twelve college audiences during the current academic year.<p>

Refuting what he calls "the liberal history lesson, " Mr. Evans said his latest book, <b>The Theme is Freedom</b>, deals with the origins of freedom in the United States and the role faith and religion played in establishing that freedom.<p>

<img alt="Mr. Evans" src="evans1.gif"><hr>
<i>Mr. Evans signs his book, <b>The Theme is Freedom</b>, for students following his speech.</i>
<hr>

Specifically, he dealt with three interrelated issues: first, where our freedom comes from; second, why we have freedom in America; and finally, how we sustain freedom.<p>

The issue of the role of faith in our founding has implications for modern political dilemmas such as prayer in school, abortion, and the so-called Religious Right.<p>

Liberals argue that faith and freedom are in conflict and that if we want freedom, we must keep religion out  of the public sphere. That line of reasoning, Mr. Evans said, is the premise for recent court decisions  banning prayer in school and forbidding any form of religious observance from public settings.<p>

According to Mr. Evans, such rulings, as well as the theory that faith and freedom are at odds, "are products of the way we are taught political and intellectual history-that is, through what I call the liberal 
history lesson."<p>

The liberal history lesson posits that freedom, philosophy, drama and other worthy practices existed in the ancient world, prior to Christianity. Mr. Evans said we are taught that in the early 5th century, the fall of classical antiquity "was followed by 1000 years of nothingness.... The Christian church ruled in an era of oppression and dictatorship."<p>

During the Renaissance, the liberals teach, classical antiquity was rediscovered, the institution of the 
church was rejected and there emerged what became the modern era's secular, rational basis for democracy,  freedom and the nation-state. Our Constitution, and the resulting rationalistic free system, is a product of the Enlightenment, according to the Left.<p>

"This is the framework," said Mr. Evans, "in which most of us, for decades, have learned our intellectual history." American history is being taught, for the most part, as a "subset" of the larger world history lesson.<p>

That lesson, according to Mr. Evans, is a "complete misstatement of the facts and of the record. It is an effort to impose secular liberal concepts on our system."<p>

There is no validity to the argument that faith and freedom are in conflict, and in reality, "They must go together, both conceptually and as a matter of history."<p>

Conceptually, Mr. Evans said, liberals argue that relativism, or the belief that there are no absolute standards, is necessary for a tolerant and just society-that a society can only be free when judgment is suspended. If that were the case, according to Mr. Evans, and there were no moral absolutes, no right or wrong, then a society could not pass judgment on Adolph Hitler. "How does one condemn any atrocity?" he asked. "All totalitarian regimes were relativist."<p>

<img alt="Mr. Evans" src="evans.gif"><hr>
<i>As part of the Henry Salvatori Distinguished Lecture Series, <b>M. Stanton Evans</b> speaks during a student luncheon, hosted by Young America's Foundation, at the Conservative Political Action Confrence.  Mr. Evans said the modern interpretation that prayer has no place in the public sphere is a travesty.  "it is an intellectual scandal and it's unconstitutional."</i><hr>

Faith and freedom must go together according to historical fact as well. In the Declaration of Independence, for instance, Thomas Jefferson wrote that it is  "self evident" that human beings are created equal. But Mr. Evans said, "If it was so evident to Jefferson, and to us, why wasn't it self evident to Aristotle, arguably the smartest man who ever lived? " Aristotle believed that some are born to be slaves and that all citizens belong to the state.<p>

According to Mr. Evans, the notion of limits on governmental power that stems from the Bible did not exist in Aristotle's time. Our Founding Fathers derived the notion that people should seek freedom rather than the bondage of a king from the Book of Samuel.<p>

Mr. Evans notes that both the Magna Carta and the Mayflower Compact are religious documents which were fundamental in the formation of our free form of government. Revisionists often say that the pilgrims who wrote the Mayflower Compact in 1620 found their inspiration for the document in John Lockerather than the Bible. Locke, however, was not born until 1632. The document is based purely on covenental theology, and subsequently, had a major impact on all of our governmental institutions with which we are familiar today.<p>

The First Amendment, Mr. Evans said, has suffered most grossly the inaccuracies of liberal revisionism. Modern history lessons, and in turn, the Supreme Court, now declare that the First Amendment was intended "to banish relizion from the public order."

According to Mr. Evans, that notion is "Orwellian and a complete inversion and falsification of our history."<p>

At the time the First Amendment was written, states established churches and even imposed religious requirements for holding pub- | lic office. We are told that Congress adopted the First Amendment in order to prohibit tax-supported prayer. Yet on September 25, 1789, one day after Congress passed the First Amendment, it passed a resolution calling on the president to declare a day of prayer and thanksgiving, which President Washington did.<p>

The modern interpretation of the Constitution, which states that prayer has no place in the public sphere, is a "travesty," according to Mr. Evans. "It is an intellectual scandal and it's unconstitutional."<p>

Mr. Evans said it is up to conservatives to recover the true history of our nation. While liberals have embraced revisionist history, conservatives must "get the basics right about the principles from which our freedoms developed."<p>

As part of the Henry Salvatori Distinguished Lecture Series, Mr. Evans' campus appearances have included, among others, <b>Canisius College</b> in New York on February 23, <b>Regent College</b> in Virginia on March 23, <b>Fordham University</b> in New York on April 5, and <b>Princeton University</b> on April 18.<p><p>

[ <a href="i-lib.html">Contents</a> ]

</body>
</html>
