<head>
<title>Campus Crisis</title>
</head>

<body background="/yaf/ground2.gif">

<h2>Campus Crisis</h2>

<h4>Deceiving Donors</h4>

Having misled alumnus <b>Lee M. Bass</b> on its plans to develop a program on Western Civilization, Yale University has agreed to return Mr. Bass' $20 million gift to the school. While the program was scheduled to begin in the fall of 1993, it was not until the spring of 1995 that Yale informed Mr. Bass that they were prepared to go ahead with the program. In the intervening years, however, Yale had scrapped the original implementation plan for the Western Civ program and appointed a new advisory committee to develop a scheme more acceptable to leftist critics. This shift occurred unbeknownst to Mr. Bass, who had been assured by Yale President <b>Richard Levin</b> that he would be kept abreast of the program's development. A skeptical Mr. Bass, aware of Yale's move toward a more multicultural approach to teaching history, asked to approve the professors scheduled to teach the course. Yale refused and has agreed to return the gift. Student <b>Pat Collins</b> said, "I'm disappointed that the university wasn't able to conduct itself in a  trustworthy way to allay the concerns of the donor."<p>

<h4>PC Strikes Again</h4>

Ironically, one week before the Supreme Court was set to hear the case of <i>Wide Awake</i>, a University of Virginia publication denied funding due to its Christian perspective, UVa struck again. This time the Student Council defunded the conservative student magazine, the <i>Virginia Advocate</i>. According to Student Council, the <i>Advocate</i> represented a "political activity." Student Council appropriates funds to leftist political organizations such as the National Organization for Women, Gay and Straight for Equality, and the Lesbian, Bisexual and Gay Student Union. UVa also funds decidedly liberal student newspapers such as the <i>University Journal</i> the <i>Declaration and Pride</i>. Student editors of the Virginia Advocate are appealing the decision to defund the paper and plan to take their case to court if necessary.<p>

<h4>Objections Raised To Communist Chair</h4>

<b>Angela Davis</b>, tenured professor of the history of consciousness at the University of California at Santa Cruz, has been named to the prestigious Presidential Chair by Jack W. Peltason, president of the university system. Her appointment has raised objections by California state senators who are concerned about Ms. Davis' "reputation for racism, violence and Communism."  As chair, Ms. Davis will have an additional $30,000 a year at her disposal, which she plans to use to develop an ethnic studies program.<p>

<h4>Strange Course Requirements</h4>

At Virginia's Tidewater Community College students taking a course in human sexuality have the option of reading five books other than their textbook or they may undertake one of the following: watch an X-rated movie, visit an adult bookstore, go to a gay bar, visit a family-planning center or an STD clinic, or speak to a member of the clergy concerning the church's philosophy regarding sexuality issues.  When a student objected to the activities the course was encouraging, the state's associate director of the State Council for Higher Education said the course sounded "perfectly legitimate" and said, "I can't imagine any student has the right to complain."<p><p>

[ <a href="i-lib.html">Contents</a> ]

</body>
