<head>
<title>Conservative Black Speakers Hit the Campus</title>
</head>

<body background="/yaf/ground2.gif">

<h2>Conservative Black Speakers Hit the Campus</h2>

<h4>Foundation Program Countering Black Racist Speakers on Campus</h4>

In response to the overwhelmingly leftist bent of Black History Month on campuses, Young America's 
Foundation initiated the Alternative Black Speakers Program. The program enables Young America's Foundation to send conservative black speakers to college campuses across the country, giving students an alternative to the often radical and irresponsible message of black lecturers appearing on campuses as part of official university programs.<p>

Young America's Foundation is offering the Alternative Black Speakers Program to students who are 
disappointed in the liberal, divisive message being promoted by their schools during Black History Month. Radicals such as <b>Joycelyn Elders</b>, former surgeon general under <b>President Clinton</b>, who recently stated that students should be taught about masturbation at an early age, and <b>Anita Hill</b> are frequent speakers on college campuses. Rap musician, <b>Ice T</b>, who sings about killing police, brought his message to Radford University in Virginia. During a lecture at West Chester University in Pennsylvania, <b>Khalid Muhammad</b> told students, "Now is the time to stand up and fight back.... There are no good crackers [white people], and if you find one, kill him before he changes. " At the University of Pennsylvania, <b>Louis Farrakhan</b> accused Jews of -"using God as a shield for [their] dirty religion.<p>

<img alt="William Allen" src="allen.gif"><hr>
<i><b>William Allen</b> talks candidly with students at Young America's Foundation's 1994 Summer Confrence.</i><hr>

<b>Stokely Carmichael</b> called for a complete revolution during a speech at the University of California at Irvine. He urged African Americans to overthrow the American capitalist society. Mr. Carmichael said, "No human advances are possible without the shedding of blood.... Student movements must have a strong wational base," he said. "They must be clear and precise. One must be willing to kill and die for it."<p>

The Foundation's experience with the Alternative Black Speakers Program has shown that there is great demand for conservative black speakers, and, while the project is entering its second year, that demand continues unabated. Young America's Foundation receives calls daily requesting information on this program.<p>

Young America's Foundation has sponsored twentyfour speeches by black conservative :-speakers. Speakers include <b>Walter Williams</b>, an economics professor at George Mason University, who speaks on free market issues; <b>Star Parker</b>, a former welfare recipient who broke free of dependency and became highly successful in business; and <b>Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas</b>, who will speak at two schools in the fall.<p>

<img alt="Star Parker" src="parker.gif"><hr>
<i><b>Star Parker</b> talks with a student at Florida State University following her remarks during Black History Month.</i><hr>

Young America's Foundation's Alternative Black Speakers Program has provided thousands of students with an opportunity to hear conservative speakers during Black History Month and throughout the year. Star Parker's appearance at Swarthmore College in December was highly successful. and
students were able to obtain cosponsorship with the "Women of Color" organization on their campus. During the speech, Ms. Parker said, "Capitalism is opportunity, it gives people vision, structure,
absolutes and order.... The American dream does not involve socialism, it involves capitalism." She 
explored the pitfalls and disincentives of the welfare state, saying, "Where else can you go that you get 
$500 a month for getting pregnant? "<p>

Florida State University conservative student activists also hosted Ms. Parker during Black History
Month. Young America's Foundation activist and FSU student, <b>Stephen Slivinski</b> said, "Star Parker was bright and articulate -- a glittering personality. She spoke with the conviction and compassion that liberals claim conservatives don't have. The audience was diverse in ideology as well as race-something that would make the affirmative action proponents proud, save for the fact that the audience showed up to be enlightened and challenged, not by dint of some governmental program."<p>

Walter Williams spoke to 650  students at Texas A&~~M University during the College Republican "Rush Week." He addressed the role of government in a free society, saying, "Expanding government is not the answer; the free market should determine where the dollars go." His address was featured an the front page of the school newspaper.<p>

Over 350 students turned out at the University of Arkansas to hear Dr. Williams, who said that the nation is headed toward more totalitarianism and governmental control. Our problems as a nation, according to Dr. Williams, are caused by "a significant departure from the principles of individual freedom that made us a rich nation to begin with Dr. Williams said that this diagnosis could carry us part of the way toward solving our national problems. "One good thing about Americans is that they never do the wrong thing for a long time." He said he is expecting the American people to change their present economic course.
At what students called the best attended lecture in years, over 400 students at Penn State University heard Dr. Williams speak. He has also spoken at Iowa State University and the University of 
Wisconsin - Milwaukee.<p>

Through the Alternative Black Speakers Program, Young America's Foundation has identified dynamic black speakers who are eager to bring a conservative message to the campuses for years to come. While 
colleges and universities instinctively bring liberal speakers to their school, Young America's Foundation is 
working daily with students to offer an alternative, conservative message from black speakers.<p><p>

[ <a href="i-lib.html">Contents</a> ]

</body>
