<html>

<title>August 22, 1996 Press Release</title>

<body>

<font size=-1>

FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
August 22, 1996<br>
CONTACT: Kristi S. Hamrick -- (202) 393-2100. For Radio: Rebecca Biles.
</font>

<p>

<center><h2>ATTENTION EDITORS AND REPORTERS:

<p>

<i>&quot;ON DRUGS<br>
THE CLINTON ADMINISTRATION'S CURIOUS<br>
SURRENDER&quot;</i></h2>

<p>

<h4>Available NOW along with other policy works
on the growing drug problem in America.</h4></center>

<p>

<b>WASHINGTON, D.C. --</b> &quot;The policy debate over the drug
problem has radically changed from one that tried to find effective
ways of keeping our children from drugs to 'harm reduction' strategies
which facilitate 'safer' drug use ... and you can see the result
of that seriously flawed switch,&quot; said Robert L. Maginnis,
drug policy analyst for the Family Research Council. The policy
expert made his comments as more evidence was unveiled this week
on the growing drug crisis in America.

<p>

&quot;Illicit drugs kill 20,000 Americans every year,&quot; Maginnis
noted. &quot;We must get serious about the life and death struggle
that casual attitudes toward drug use ignore.&quot;

<p>

Other policy papers available from the Family Research Council
looking at drug use:

<p><ul>

<li>&quot;<a href="/townhall/FRC/perspective/pv96b3dr.html">New Commander for 
Three-Front Drug War</a>&quot; on General Barry McCaffrey
