<title>November 20, 1995 Press Release</title>
<body>
<font size=-1>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
November 20, 1995<br>
CONTACT: Kristi S. Hamrick -- 202-393-2100. For Radio: Kristin Hansen.
</font>
<p>
<center><h3>DEMOCRATS AND REPUBLICANS AGREE:<br>
THIS BUDGET DEBATE IS ABOUT WHETHER GOVERNMENT SHOULD BE SOCIETY'S
PROBLEM SOLVER
<p>
CAN WE DEPEND ON A WORLD WITHOUT WELFARE?
<p>
WILL PEOPLE VOLUNTEER AND GIVE WHEN THE &quot;SAFETY NET&quot;
CHANGES?
<p>
FOR THESE QUESTIONS: TWO ANSWERS</h3></center>
<p>
On Tuesday, Nov. 21 at 9:30 a.m. in the Main Lounge of  the National
Press Club Family Research Council will release original polling
data on what Americans believe about changes in the fabric of
the safety net. What do Americans think about changes in welfare
and about the private community standing in the gap for people
in need?
<p>
<center><h4>AND COMING SOON:</h4></center>
<p>
On Wednesday, Dec. 13 from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. at the Willard Hotel,
Family Research Council will host a symposium on <B>A WORLD
WITHOUT WELFARE</B>. A star-studded cast from the policy and
philosophical worlds -- from think tanks to the grassroots --
will come together from across the country to discuss answers
to society's toughest questions, <B>AND</B>, to provide some answers
on how to transition from a welfare state.
<p>
Experts in their fields, speakers will include: Dr. Michael Novak,
David Frum, Dr. Marvin Olasky, Father Robert Sirico, John Walters,
Robert Rector and many more.
<p>
