<html>

<title>Daily Commentary - December 3, 1996</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
December 3, 1996</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

While you and I were enjoying our Thanksgiving turkey, a
judge in California was busy putting Proposition 209 on the chopping
block.  Through Prop. 209, California voters dismantled the state's
system of racial preferences in hiring and college admissions.
The judge issued what's called a &quot;temporary restraining
order,&quot; keeping the racial spoils system in place for now.
He claimed that Prop. 209 probably violates the 14th amendment's
guarantee of equal protection.  But that's exactly what Prop.
209 <i>does</i> guarantee:  equal protection for all citizens
regardless of race or gender.

<p>

Now whatever you think of affirmative action itself, this
case is yet another example of judicial tyranny.  In Colorado,
it was a ban on special rights for homosexuals.  In Washington
state, a law against assisted suicide.  In each case, the courts
overturned the will of the people on a hotly contested issue.
The real question we must ask is:  how can self-government survive
as our courts shrink our liberty?  To answer that question is
to determine the fate of our republic.

<p>

For the Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with
today's Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call
1-800-225-4008.  That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

<p>

<center><b>
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/radio/wwold.html.cgi#current">Last Month's Commentaries</a>] 
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/radio/wwdaily.html.cgi#current">This Month's Commentaries</a>]
</b></center>

<p>

