<html>

<title>Daily Commentary - December 6, 1996</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
December 6, 1996</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

The December chill has set in around the city of Washington.
With Congress out of town and President Clinton embarking on
a second term, the news hereabouts would typically be dominated
by the White House.  But it's been strangely silent at 1600 Pennsylvania
Ave.  Maybe it's the President's bad case of laryngitis although
most people who know Bill Clinton say not even that can keep him
from talking.

<p>

Just think: a month ago, as the Presidential campaign was
in high gear, the White House was reportedly simmering with ideas.
There were new proposals every day to counter education decline
and domestic abuse.  With all of that energy and excitement, staffing
the President's Cabinet should be easy.  But instead the President
only in the last 24 hours has been able to make appointments of
new officials to take us across that bridge to the 21st century.

<p>

Maybe the White House will shake off these December doldrums,
but it may also be that Bill Clinton is undergoing the curse of
the second term.  During this century, second terms have been
notoriously full of failure, indecision and scandal. Will that
be Bill Clinton's fate, too?  Only time will tell.

<p>

For the Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with
today's Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call
1-800-225-4008.  That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

<p>

<center><b>
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/radio/wwold.html.cgi#current">Last Month's Commentaries</a>] 
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/radio/wwdaily.html.cgi#current">This Month's Commentaries</a>]
</b></center>

<p>

<HR SIZE = 3>

