<html>

<title>Daily Commentary - December 10, 1996</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
December 10, 1996</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

This week, more disturbing news was unveiled about the problem
called Gulf War Syndrome.  If you haven't been following this
story in detail, it involves nearly one hundred thousand American
veterans of the war against Saddam Hussein.  These veterans are
experiencing a wide variety of ailments, including birth defects
among their children, and a dispute is raging over whether exposure
to Iraqi chemical weapons is to blame.  For six years now, our
government has dragged its feet about getting to the bottom of
this.  The latest word is that key documents central to this investigation
are missing.

<p>

I'm neither a military nor medical expert, but foot-dragging
and ineptitude on matters like this are unacceptable.  The Pentagon
should be seeking answers to the nagging questions about Gulf
War Syndrome with the same vigor that it prosecuted the fight
against Iraq.  These young men, and now women, who answered their
country's call were heroes and heroines overseas.  Now our government
is acting like they are only hypochondriacs.  They deserve better
-- much better.

<p>

For the Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with
today's Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call
1-800-225-4008.  That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

