<html>

<title>Daily Commentary - December 12, 1996</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
December 12, 1996</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

American families want to trust their government in matters
great and small, but sometimes it isn't easy.  As we found with
the recent controversy over air bags, federal officials knew more
about the hazards of these devices than they were willing to tell
us -- supposedly for our own good.  The same goes for Gulf War
syndrome -- the possible exposure of our Desert Storm soldiers
to chemical weapons.

<p>

There was shocking testimony on Capitol Hill this week. 
It now seems clear that military commanders failed to pursue findings
by their own trained personnel that chemical weapon exposure had
taken place.  The British defense ministry has now publicly apologized
for its failure to follow through on the issue too.

<p>

These incidents have a common thread -- a national nanny
government that thinks it must shape and limit what the people
know.  Maybe you've had a similar experience with public officials
-- with the IRS, or with some environmental rule.  Practices like
these create an unhealthy gap between citizen and government.
That just isn't America -- here you have to earn your trust.

<p>

For the Family Research Council this is Gary Bauer with today's
Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call 1-800-225-4008.
That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

<p>

