<html>

<title>Daily Commentary - December 19, 1996</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
December 19, 1996</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

Outside the White House press room, there is a gallery of
famous drawings by Norman Rockwell.  Rockwell portrayed reporters
as a classic group of working stiffs, lovable Joe's just waiting
for the right story to come along.  Just how far that image of
the press has faded from the public mind is obvious in a new Harris
Poll.

<p>

By large margins, the poll found, Americans believe reporters
are, get your paper and pencil ready, politically biased, obnoxious,
negative, sensational, and inaccurate.  And if that isn't enough,
the public also believes that reporters have too much influence,
ignore people's privacy, overlook their own errors, show too much
violence, and don't much care about people.  This is hardly good
news for our free press.  The public has about as much faith in
them as it would in Attila the Hun.

<p>

And the Harris Poll also had some hot tips for reporters.
By similar majorities, Americans want the media to root out corruption
in office and to protect the public from abuses of power.  In
short, to be good citizens first.  Now it seems to me that isn't
too much to ask.

<p>

For the Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with
today's Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call
1-800-225-4008.  That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

<p>

