<html>

<title>Daily Commentary - December 25, 1996</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
December 25, 1996</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

On Christmas Day, we celebrate what might be called the &quot;mundane
miracle.&quot;  It was the most ordinary of events:  the birth
of a baby.  But it was the most impossible of miracles, too: 
the incarnation of God Himself.

<p>

The birth of that baby split human history in two.  Nothing
will ever be the same on this earth.  On an infinitely smaller
scale, the birth of any baby has the same effect on human habits.
Having a child changes us.  Suddenly, the carefree single becomes
caregiving father or mother.  Issues that didn't matter before
suddenly matter a lot --- from personal safety, to what's on TV,
to pornography -- right on down to regular mealtimes.

<p>

Such is the power of a baby.  But today, as more and more
of us turn our back on the child born in Bethlehem, our backs
are turned on other babies, too.  Babies slain in the womb or
left in dumpsters with the other debris of our too-fast times.
How foolish we are to reject new life -- for what is Christmas,
but the eternal promise of new life in Christ?

<p>

For the Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with
the today's Washington Watch.  For more information about us,
call 1-800-225-4008.  That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

<p>

