<html>

<title>Daily Commentary - December 27, 1996</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
December 27, 1996</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

Have you heard the news out of Oakland, California?  In that
city, the school board has done something truly idiotic.  They
decided to designate the language of certain minority students
as a foreign language.  The term for this language is &quot;Ebonics,&quot;
but in fact Ebonics is nothing more than English spoken poorly.

<p>

By getting the language patterns of these urban kids established
as a foreign tongue, the school board hoped to take advantage
of bilingual education money.  You heard me right.  Naturally,
the school board's action caused a firestorm.  It's tempting to
joke that all of this is merely a semantic dispute.  These young
kids obviously need help in learning to speak, read, and write
standard English, so who cares where the money comes from?  But
something deeper is at work here.

<p>

This issue really concerns false presumptions about who can
learn.  The Oakland school board is selling its own black students
short.  By doing so, it is limiting their horizons and their job
prospects.  The word for that is &quot;sad&quot; -- in any language.

<p>

For the Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with
today's Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call
1-800-225-4008.  That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

<p>

